  "prompt": "What's the difference between an appositive and subject compliment?",
  "response": "An appositive and a subject complement both provide additional information about a noun in a sentence, but they do so in different ways and serve different grammatical roles.\n\n### Appositive:\n- **Definition**: An appositive is a noun or noun phrase that renames or provides additional information about another noun adjacent to it.\n- **Usage**: Appositives are often set off by commas when they are non-restrictive (not essential to the meaning of the sentence). \n- **Example**: In the sentence \"My brother, a talented musician, is coming to visit,\" the phrase \"a talented musician\" is an appositive that gives more information about \"my brother.\"\n\n### Subject Complement:\n- **Definition**: A subject complement is a word or phrase (which can be a noun, pronoun, or adjective) that follows a linking verb and provides more information about the subject.\n- **Usage**: Subject complements are essential to the meaning of the sentence and complete the subject's meaning.\n- **Example**: In the sentence \"She is a doctor,\" the word \"doctor\" serves as a subject complement that identifies or describes \"she.\"\n\n### Summary:\n- **Function**: An appositive renames a noun, while a subject complement describes or identifies the subject of the sentence.\n- **Structure**: Appositives can be set off by commas; subject complements follow linking verbs without commas. \n\nUnderstanding the distinction between these two components can help in constructing clear and grammatically correct sentences.",
